item.label: Basilar sulcus
item.name: Basilar sulcus
item.description: The basilar sulcus is a midline groove on the ventral or anterior aspect of the basilar portion of the pons. The basilar artery lies within this sulcus.

item.label: Cerebellopontine angle
item.name: Cerebellopontine angle
item.description: The cerebellopontine angle is the point at which the cerebellum meets the junction of the pons with the medulla.  The facial and vestibulocochlear nerves are located at this point.

item.label: Facial colliculus
item.name: Facial colliculus
item.description: The facial colliculus is a surface bump or elevation on either side of the midline in the floor of the fourth ventricle in the caudal pons.  It is formed by the facial motor nerve fibers passing over the abducens nucleus. It is part of the median eminence located medial to the sulcus limitans in the floor of the fourth ventricle

item.label: Sulcus Limitans
item.name: Sulcus Limitans
item.description: The sulcus limitans is a shallow groove in the floor of the fourth ventricle that demarcates sensory cranial nerve nuclei (laterally) from motor cranial nerve nuclei (medially). Embryonically, it is a longitudinal groove extending along the length of the brain stem and spinal cord, separating alar plate (future sensory nuclei) from basal plate (future motor nuclei.)

item.label: Cerebellum
item.name: Cerebellum
item.description: The cerebellum is sometimes referred to as the 'small' brain.  It is located within the posterior fossa, superior to the brain stem. It consists of a finely convoluted cortical surface of folia, a central core of white matter (AKA medullary center) and four paired deep nuclei (dentate, emboliform, fastigial and globose) embedded within the white matter core. The cerebellum functions in the planning and coordination of movement.

item.label: Cerebellar cortex
item.name: Cerebellar cortex
item.description: The outer cortical surface of the cerebellum is folded into fine-caliber ridges called folia.  This cortex consists of three layers, an outer molecular layer, an inner granular layer and a Purkinje cell layer in the middle at the junction of the molecular and granular layers.

item.label: Deep cerebellar nuclei
item.name: Deep cerebellar nuclei
item.description: The deep nuclei of the cerebellum (dentate, globus, emboliform and fastigial nuclei) are located within the white matter core of the cerebellum. While they receive afferent input from extra-cerebellar sources, their main input is from the Purkinje cells of the cerebellar cortex. Their output constitutes the primary output of the cerebellum, per se, and travels primarily in the superior cerebellar peduncle to terminate in the motor part of thalamus plus in the red nuclei.

item.label: Dentate nucleus
item.name: Dentate nucleus
item.description: The dentate nucleus is the largest and most lateral of the deep cerebellar nuclei. It appears as a highly-convoluted draw-string purse with a small opening or hilus from which its efferent fibers exit on their way to the superior cerebellar peduncle. Afferents to the dentate nucleus are primarily from the neocerbellar cortex or lateral aspects of the hemispheres. Efferents terminate primarily in the ventral lateral nucleus of thalamus. Because of a similar shape, it can be confused with the inferior olivary nucleus found in the medulla.

item.label: Emboliform nucleus
item.name: Emboliform nucleus
item.description: The emboliform nucleus is one of the deep nuclei of the cerebellum located medial to the dentate nucleus and lateral to the globose nucleus. In non-human species it is combined with the globose nucleus as a single nuclear mass and called the 'interposed' nucleus or 'nucleus interpositus'; this term is commonly used in human neuroanatomy as well. It receives input from the paravermal zone of cerebellar cortex and projects its output via the superior cerebellar peduncle to terminate in the ventral lateral nucleus of thalamus and the red nucleus.

item.label: Fastigial nucleus
item.name: Fastigial nucleus
item.description: The fastigial nucleus is the most medially located of the deep nuclei of the cerebellum. Its primary input is from the vermis of the cerebellum and it projects its output bilaterally to the vestibular nuclei and reticular formation. Through these brainstem connections, the cerebellum can influence lower motor neurons via the vestibulospinal and reticulospinal tracts.

item.label: Globose nucleus
item.name: Globose nucleus
item.description: The globose nucleus is one of the deep nuclei of the cerebellum located between the fastigial and emboliform nuclei. In non-human species it is combined with the emboliform nucleus as a single nuclear mass and called the 'interposed' nucleus or 'nucleus interpositus'; this term is commonly used in human neuroanatomy as well. It receives input from the paravermal zone of cerebellar cortex and projects its output via the superior cerebellar peduncle to terminate in the ventral lateral nucleus of thalamus and the red nucleus.

item.label: Cerebellar peduncles
item.name: Cerebellar peduncles
item.description: There are three pair of cerebellar peduncles that consist of nerve fibers connecting the cerebellum with the brainstem and elsewhere.  Included are the paired superior, middle and inferior cerebellar peduncles.

item.label: Inferior cerebellar peduncle
item.name: Inferior cerebellar peduncle
item.description: The inferior cerebellar peduncle is AKA the restiform body. Located on the lateral aspect of the medulla, it includes multiple tracts afferent to the cerebellum including the uncrossed dorsal or posterior spinocerebellar, cuneocerebellar, vestibulocerebellar, reticulocerebellar and crossed olivocerebellar. It also includes some cerebellar output tracts such as those projecting to the reticular formation and the vestibular nuclei.

item.label: Juxtarestiform body
item.name: Juxtarestiform body
item.description: The Juxtarestiform body is a portion fo the inferior cerebellar peduncle that carries both afferent and efferent fibers between the vestibular nuclei, the fastigial nuclei and the flocculonodular lobe. Thus it carries information important to balance and equilibriuum.

item.label: Middle cerebellar peduncle
item.name: Middle cerebellar peduncle
item.description: The middle cerebellar peduncle consists exclusively of pontocerebellar tract fibers that take their origin from pontine nuclei in the contralateral basilar pons. Thus, it carries afferent information to cerebellum from the contralateral cerebral cortex via the corticopontine to pontine nuclei to pontocerebellar tract.

item.label: Pons, tegmentum
item.name: Pons, tegmentum
item.description: The tegmentum or tegmental pons forms the dorsal aspect of the pons.  It is continuous with the tegmental portions of both the midbrain and medulla. Includes cranial nerve nuclei and clinically important sensory tracts [medial lemniscal, spinothalamic, lateral lemniscal]. The rostral aspect of the fourth ventricle is located on it dorsal surface.

item.label: Pons, basilar
item.name: Pons, basilar
item.description: The basilar pons is AKA the basal pons. It is the ventral portion of the pons that includes the following important elements that are primarily involved in motor control: corticospinal, corticobulbar, corticospinal and pontocerebellar tracts plus the pontine nuclei. Thus, it serves as a conduit for descending motor pathways from cerebral cortex to the pons, medulla and spinal cord. In addition, it connects the cerebral cortex with the cerebellum via synapses of the corticopontine fibers on pontine nuclei that then give origin to the pontocerebellar fibers which terminate in cerebellum.

item.label: Abducens nucleus
item.name: Abducens nucleus
item.description: The abducens nucleus contains the lower motor neurons of the abducens nerve that innervate the ipsilateral lateral rectus muscle. It also contains interneurons that project through the contralateral medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF) to communicate with the contralateral medial rectus neurons in the oculomotor complex; these interneurons are instrumental for conjugate horizontal eye movements. The abducens nucleus is located close to the floor of the fourth ventricle beneath the elevation known as the facial colliculus. The facial motor nerve fibers that innervate the muscles of facial expression, travel over or superior to the abducens nucleus and beneath the facial colliculus.

item.label: Facial motor nucleus
item.name: Facial motor nucleus
item.description: The facial motor nucleus is a cranial nerve nucleus located in the caudal pons containing the lower motor neurons that innervate the ipsilateral skeletal muscles derived embryologically from the second pharyngeal arch, i.e. muscles of facial expression, posterior belly of the digastric, stylohyoid and stapedius.

item.label: Pontine nuclei
item.name: Pontine nuclei
item.description: The pontine nuclei are a large number of small nuclei located in the basilar portion of the pons. They are scattered among many nerve fibers in this area. They receive input from the ipsilateral cerebral cortex via corticopontine fibers that travel to the pons via the internal capsule and cerebral crus; they give origin to pontocerebellar fibers whose axons cross the midline and enter the cerebellum contralateral to their origin

item.label: Pontobulbar body
item.name: Pontobulbar body
item.description: The pontobulbar body is located in the cerebellopontine angle caudal to the cochlear nuclear complex.  It is adjacent to both the seventh and eighth cranial nerves.

item.label: Reticular formation
item.name: Reticular formation
item.description: Reticular formation is the central region of the brainstem tegmentum (medulla, pons, midbrain).  It is a network of interconnected nuclei and nerve fibers. Due to its widespread afferent and efferent connections, it serves a major integrating function. It gives origin to clinically significant tracts such as the reticulospinal and raphe spinal. It contains the cardiovascular and respiratory centers so critical to survival. It is also an important component of the sleep/wake cycle via is role in the ascending reticular activating system.

item.label: Superior olivary nucleus
item.name: Superior olivary nucleus
item.description: The superior olivary nucleus is located in the tegmentum of the caudal pons near the rostral end of the facial motor nucleus. This nucleus is part of the auditory pathway and is NOT part of the inferior olivary complex of nuclei. The superior olivary nucleus receives auditory input from both ears and gives origin to many of the lateral lemniscal fibers. It is also the origin of efferent fibers to the contralateral organ of Corti where it is able to modulate hair cell activity.

item.label: Trigeminal spinal nucleus
item.name: Trigeminal spinal nucleus
item.description: The trigeminal spinal nucleus is AKA the spinal trigeminal nucleus. It is a portion of the trigeminal sensory nuclei that exists as a longitudinal column of cells within the lateral aspect of the caudal pons and medulla. Caudally, it merges with the dorsal horn of the spinal cord (particularly, the substantia gelatinosa); rostrally it merges into the trigeminal main sensory nucleus. It consists of second-order sensory neurons that receive primarily pain and temperature information from the head via input from the trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) tract. Efferents from this nucleus terminate in the contralateral ventral posterior medial nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Vestibular nucleus
item.name: Vestibular nucleus
item.description: The vestibular nuclei are a group of four sub-nuclei present bilaterally in the floor of the fourth ventricle at the junction of the pons and medulla. The four sub-nuclei are the inferior, lateral, medial and superior. These nuclei receive input from the vestibular organs (cristae of the semicircular ducts and maculae of the utricle and saccule of the inner ear) via the eighth cranial nerve. These nuclei project to the nuclei innervating the extraocular muscles via the medial longitudinal fasciculus, to the cerebellum, to the spinal cord, thalamus and reticular formation.

item.label: Central tegmental tract
item.name: Central tegmental tract
item.description: The central tegmental tract is a large, heterogeneous tract traveling through the central or tegmental portion of the brainstem. It includes descending fibers from the red nucleus to the ipsilateral inferior olivary nucleus, ascending taste fibers from the rostral solitary nucleus as well as multiple inputs and outputs of the reticular formation.

item.label: Corticospinal, -bulbar, -pontine trs
item.name: Corticospinal,-bulbar, -pontine trs
item.description: These descending motor tracts originate in the cerebral cortex and then travel through the posterior limb of the internal capsule, the cerebral crus of the midbrain, the basilar portion of the pons and the pyramids of the medulla.  Sometimes this group of tracts is referred to as the pyramidal tract or system.  It includes the corticospinal, corticobulbar and corticopontine tracts.  The corticopontine fibers terminate at the level of the pons; therefore, the pyramids contain only corticospinal and corticobulbar fibers while only the corticospinal fibers continue into the spinal cord.  There are other subcortical descending motor tracts (reticulospinal and vestibulospinal) that originate in the reticular formation and vestibular nuclei of the brain stem.

item.label: Dorsal longitudinal fasciculus
item.name: Dorsal longitudinal fasciculus
item.description: The dorsal longitudinal fasciculus consists of ascending and descending fibers traveling through the periaqueductal and periventricular gray matter, connecting the hypothalamus to the reticular formation and to preganglionic autonomic neurons.

item.label: Inferior cerebellar peduncle
item.name: Inferior cerebellar peduncle2
item.description: The inferior cerebellar peduncle is AKA the restiform body. Located on the lateral aspect of the medulla, it includes multiple tracts afferent to the cerebellum including the uncrossed dorsal or posterior spinocerebellar, cuneocerebellar, vestibulocerebellar, reticulocerebellar and crossed olivocerebellar. It also includes some cerebellar output tracts such as those projecting to the reticular formation and the vestibular nuclei.

item.label: Juxtarestiform body
item.name: Juxtarestiform body_1
item.description: The Juxtarestiform body is a portion fo the inferior cerebellar peduncle that carries both afferent and efferent fibers between the vestibular nuclei, the fastigial nuclei and the flocculonodular lobe. Thus it carries information important to balance and equilibriuum.

item.label: Lateral lemniscus
item.name: Lateral leminscus
item.description: The lateral lemniscus is a portion of the auditory pathway that transmits auditory information from the ipsilateral and contralateral (primarily) cochlear nuclei and superior olivary nuclei to the nucleus of the inferior colliculus.

item.label: Medial lemniscus
item.name: Medial lemniscus
item.description: The medial lemniscus is the primary ascending tract carrying tactile, vibratory and proprioceptive information from the body through the brainstem. Cells of origin are in the contralateral cuneate and gracile nuclei; termination is in the ventral posterior lateral nucleus of the thalamus. Comparable input from the head is carried in trigeminothalamic tract fibers that accompany the medial lemniscus but terminate in the ventral posterior medial nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
item.name: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
item.description: The medial longitudinal fasciculus is an important ascending fiber bundle involved in the coordination of horizontal eye movements through its origin in the vestibular nuclei and termination in the oculomotor and abducens nuclei. It is an important component of the VOR (vestibulo-ocular) reflex. A descending component of this tract (AKA medial vestibulospinal tract) travels to cervical levels of the cord and is involved in turning of the head in response to vestibular stimulation.

item.label: Middle cerebellar peduncle
item.name: Middle cerebellar peduncle2
item.description: The middle cerebellar peduncle consists exclusively of pontocerebellar tract fibers that take their origin from pontine nuclei in the contralateral basilar pons. Thus, it carries afferent information to cerebellum from the contralateral cerebral cortex via the corticopontine to pontine nuclei to pontocerebellar tract.

item.label: Pontocerebellar fibers
item.name: Pontocerebellar fibers
item.description: The pontine nuclei in the basal or basilar portion of the pons are the origin of the pontocerebellar tract. The tract crosses the midline at the level of the pons to travel as the middle cerebellar peduncle to terminate in the cerebellum contralateral to the cell bodies of origin.

item.label: Spinocerebellar tract, ventral
item.name: Spinocerebellar tract, ventral
item.description: The ventral or anterior spinocerebellar tract carries proprioceptive information from neurons in the dorsal aspect of the ventral horn in the thoracic-lumbar spinal cord to the ipsilateral cerebellum. The tract decussates in the ventral white commissure near its origin and is then located in the ventral-lateral aspect of the lateral column of the spinal cord, contralateral to the side of input. This tract takes a circuitous route to cerebellum via the superior cerebellum peduncle and recrosses the midline within the white matter of the cerebellum so that it terminates ipsilateral to the original side of input. The information in this tract comes from proprioceptors in the ipsilateral lower extremity that send their input via large diameter primary afferents to terminate or synapse in the dorsal aspect of the ventral horn.

item.label: Spinothalamic tract
item.name: Spinothalamic tract
item.description: The spinothalamic tract is primarily responsible for transmitting nociceptive (pain) and temperature information from the body. Small diameter primary afferents (first order neurons) bring the pain and temperature information into the ipsilateral dorsal horn where they synapse on the cells of origin of the spinothalamic tract. The second order neurons in the dorsal horn send their axons across the midline in the ventral white commissure so that the spinothalmamic tract ascends in the anterolateral portion of the spinal cord contralateral to the side of input of the information. This tract terminates in the ventral posterior lateral nucleus (VPL) of thalamus. From this thalamic nucleus, the information is carried to the primary somatosensory cerebral cortex where the sensation is consciously perceived.

item.label: Tectospinal tract
item.name: Tectospinal tract
item.description: The tectospinal tract originates in the superior colliculus and terminates in the cervical spinal cord. Its fibers end via interneurons on ventral horn neurons that primarily supply muscles in the neck.

item.label: Trigeminal spinal tract
item.name: Trigeminal spinal tract
item.description: The trigeminal spinal tract is AKA spinal trigeminal tract. It consists of small-diameter primary afferent nerve fibers carrying primarily pain and temperature information from the head via the trigeminal nerve (primarily) as well as the facial and glossopharyngeal nerves. The trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) tract fibers synapse in the trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) nucleus. Note that in the transition region from spinal cord to medulla, Lissauer's tract becomes continuous with the trigeminal spinal tract.

item.label: Abducens nucleus
item.name: Abducens nucleus_1
item.description: The abducens nucleus contains the lower motor neurons of the abducens nerve that innervate the ipsilateral lateral rectus muscle. It also contains interneurons that project through the contralateral medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF) to communicate with the contralateral medial rectus neurons in the oculomotor complex; these interneurons are instrumental for conjugate horizontal eye movements. The abducens nucleus is located close to the floor of the fourth ventricle beneath the elevation known as the facial colliculus. The facial motor nerve fibers that innervate the muscles of facial expression, travel over or superior to the abducens nucleus and beneath the facial colliculus.

item.label: Facial motor nucleus
item.name: Facial motor nucleus2
item.description: The facial motor nucleus is a cranial nerve nucleus located in the caudal pons containing the lower motor neurons that innervate the ipsilateral skeletal muscles derived embryologically from the second pharyngeal arch, i.e. muscles of facial expression, posterior belly of the digastric, stylohyoid and stapedius.

item.label: Facial nerve
item.name: Facial nerve
item.description: The facial or seventh cranial nerve has both sensory and motor components which enter/exit the brain stem in the cerebellopontine angle with the vestibulocochlear nerve. The most important sensory component carries taste from the anterior 2/3rds of the tongue; motor components innervate the skeletal muscles of facial expression, stapedius, etc. as well as provide the parasympathetic preganglionic fibers that control secretion of the submandibular, sublingual and lacrimal glands.

item.label: Genu of facial nerve
item.name: Genu of facial nerve
item.description: The genu of the facial nerve (AKA the internal genu of the facial nerve) is that portion of the facial nerve that passes medial to the abducens nucleus in its unusual course through the tegmentum of the pons.

item.label: Trigeminal spinal tract
item.name: Trigeminal spinal tract2
item.description: The trigeminal spinal tract is AKA spinal trigeminal tract. It consists of small-diameter primary afferent nerve fibers carrying primarily pain and temperature information from the head via the trigeminal nerve (primarily) as well as the facial and glossopharyngeal nerves. The trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) tract fibers synapse in the trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) nucleus. Note that in the transition region from spinal cord to medulla, Lissauer's tract becomes continuous with the trigeminal spinal tract.

item.label: Trigeminal spinal nucleus
item.name: Trigeminal spinal nucleus_1
item.description: The trigeminal spinal nucleus is AKA the spinal trigeminal nucleus. It is a portion of the trigeminal sensory nuclei that exists as a longitudinal column of cells within the lateral aspect of the caudal pons and medulla. Caudally, it merges with the dorsal horn of the spinal cord (particularly, the substantia gelatinosa); rostrally it merges into the trigeminal main sensory nucleus. It consists of second-order sensory neurons that receive primarily pain and temperature information from the head via input from the trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) tract. Efferents from this nucleus terminate in the contralateral ventral posterior medial nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Vestibulocochlear nerve
item.name: Vestibulocochlear nerve
item.description: The vestibulocochlear nerve is AKA the statoacoustic nerve. This eighth cranial nerve enters the brainstem at the cerebellopontine angle. It carries information from the hair cell receptors in the organ of Corti of the cochlear duct as well as from the vestibular organs (cristae of the semicircular ducts and maculae of the utricle and saccule of the inner ear).

item.label: Vestibular nucleus
item.name: Vestibular nucleus_1
item.description: The vestibular nuclei are a group of four sub-nuclei present bilaterally in the floor of the fourth ventricle at the junction of the pons and medulla. The four sub-nuclei are the inferior, lateral, medial and superior. These nuclei receive input from the vestibular organs (cristae of the semicircular ducts and maculae of the utricle and saccule of the inner ear) via the eighth cranial nerve. These nuclei project to the nuclei innervating the extraocular muscles via the medial longitudinal fasciculus, to the cerebellum, to the spinal cord, thalamus and reticular formation.

item.label: Fourth ventricle
item.name: Fourth ventricle
item.description: The fourth ventricle is a rhomboid-shaped space located superior to the pons and medulla. The roof of the fourth ventricle is formed by the inferior and superior medullary vela plus the cerebellum. Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) enters the fourth ventricle from the third ventricle via the cerebral aqueduct. CSF exits the fourth ventricle into the subarachnoid space via the medial foramen of Magendie, located in the roof of the fourth ventricle, and the two lateral foramina of Luschka, located at the most lateral aspect of the fourth ventricle, i.e. in the lateral recess of the fourth ventricle, bilaterally.  The choroid plexus is located in the roof of the fourth ventricle, beneath the inferior medullary velum.  The choroid plexus extends outside of the fourth ventricle through the foramina of Luschka, where it can be visualized in the subarachnoid space.

item.label: Sulcus Limitans
item.name: Sulcus Limitans2
item.description: The sulcus limitans is a shallow groove in the floor of the fourth ventricle that demarcates sensory cranial nerve nuclei (laterally) from motor cranial nerve nuclei (medially). Embryonically, it is a longitudinal groove extending along the length of the brain stem and spinal cord, separating alar plate (future sensory nuclei) from basal plate (future motor nuclei.)
